<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900821-0011</DOCNO><DOCID>900821-0011.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   Business and Finance</HL><DATE>08/21/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   BUDGET GAP PROJECTIONS for next year are widening by tensof billions of dollars because of higher defense spending andan economic slowdown resulting from the Mideast crisis, U.S.officials say. A record deficit of $250 billion to $300billion is likely, which could force severe Gramm-Rudmanspending cuts. Bush, meanwhile, said he will &quot;oppose thedefense budget slashers.&quot;   ---</LP><TEXT>   OPEC rejected a call by Saudi Arabia and Venezuela for anemergency meeting, leaving them free to pump more oil ontheir own. The group may still meet informally. Crude pricesclimbed further yesterday, and gasoline futures surged.   ---   Interco agreed tentatively to give bondholders 95% of thetroubled furniture and shoe company's common stock in a debtswap, plus the right to approve a new slate of directors.   ---   Data General plans to lay off at least 2,000, or 17%, ofits employees, company insiders said. Steep losses at thecomputer maker are prompting the latest round of cutbacks.   ---   First Interstate Bancorp suspended its dividendreinvestment plan, which was intended to help rebuild thecompany's capital base.   ---   Boeing received $650 million in firm aircraft orders fromAll Nippon Airways. The Japanese carrier also took out newoptions to buy $3 billion more of the Seattle firm's jets.   ---   RJR Nabisco's recent $2.25 billion loan is getting a coolreception from the regional and foreign banks asked to takeon some of the debt. The smaller banks want more of thesizable fees paid to the original lenders.   ---   Blue-chip stock prices rose in thin trading, but smallerissues didn't fare as well. The Dow Jones industrials rose11.64 points. Bond prices were flat, while the dollar endedmixed.   ---   Some individual investors are optimistic about the outlookfor stocks, showing a confidence not common among themarket's professionals.   ---   Northrop's accord in February to plead guilty to fakingtest data called for the U.S. to drop its criminalinvestigation of at least 11 other areas.   ---   Soybean oil futures traders are reporting rumors that onefirm is trying to corner the market, a year after authoritiesacted to block a suspected bid to dominate the soybeanmarket.   ---   Volvo unveiled a new top model, as Swedish car makersprepare for Japanese competition in Europe.   ---   The Cirrus and Plus networks of automated tellers agreedto give each other's customers access to their machines. Butindividual banks may opt not to participate in the plan.   ---   Denison Mines posted an $84.9 million second-quarter loss,after the Toronto company wrote down half of its oil and gasassets and provided for the cost of reducing its work force.   ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 129,630,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials2656.44, up 11.64; transportation 930.29, up 6.38; utilities201.46, up 0.32.   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3337.25, up0.82.   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 134.23, off 0.22;spot index 133.48, off 0.35.   Dollar: 146.44 yen, off 1.14; 1.5650 marks, up 0.0155.</TEXT></DOC>